# project

- project is set up and ready for development

# requirements

## user-constraints
- project slug is naiou @implemented
- local project lives at /home/everlier/code/naiou @implemented

## cli
- label: package metadata exposes a naiou executable that launches src/main.ts and build scripts emit a naiou binary
  command: node -e "const p=require(\"./package.json\"); process.exit(p.name===\"naiou\" && p.type===\"module\" && p.bin?.naiou===\"src/main.ts\" && p.scripts?.start===\"bun run src/main.ts\" && p.scripts?.build===\"sh scripts/build.sh\" && /bun build --compile src\/main\.ts --outfile naiou/.test(p.scripts?.[\"build:ts\"]||\"\") ? 0 : 1)"
  tags: [implemented]
- label: src/cli.ts uses util.parseArgs to parse --help, --version, and default interactive launch behavior
  command: test -f src/cli.ts && rg -q "parseArgs" src/cli.ts && rg -q "help" src/cli.ts && rg -q "version" src/cli.ts
  tags: [implemented]

## scaffold
- the Bun TypeScript scaffold mirrors skilled package, tsconfig, build script, cli parseArgs, app root/input, and theme-token patterns without skilled dashboard logic @implemented
- label: the scaffold includes tsconfig.json configured for Bun-style TypeScript with ESNext target, preserved modules, bundler resolution, noEmit, strict, noUncheckedIndexedAccess, and noFallthroughCasesInSwitch
  command: test -f tsconfig.json && rg -q "ESNext" tsconfig.json && rg -q "moduleResolution.: .bundler|moduleResolution\": \"bundler" tsconfig.json && rg -q "noEmit" tsconfig.json && rg -q "strict" tsconfig.json && rg -q "noUncheckedIndexedAccess" tsconfig.json && rg -q "noFallthroughCasesInSwitch" tsconfig.json
  tags: [implemented]
- label: scripts/build.sh compiles src/main.ts with bun build --compile and writes the executable to ./naiou
  command: test -f scripts/build.sh && rg -q "bun build --compile src/main.ts --outfile naiou" scripts/build.sh
  tags: [implemented]
- label: src/app.ts owns the OpenTUI renderer lifecycle and key input subscriptions while src/hyperspace.ts owns visual rendering and resize handling
  command: test -f src/app.ts && test -f src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "createCliRenderer" src/app.ts && rg -q "keyInput" src/app.ts && ! rg -q "renderer\.root|Box\(" src/app.ts && rg -q "renderer\.on\(\"resize\"" src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "setSize" src/hyperspace.ts
  tags: [implemented]
- label: src/theme.ts centralizes reusable color tokens including muted grey, yes green, no red, star colors, and background color
  command: test -f src/theme.ts && rg -q "muted" src/theme.ts && rg -q "yes" src/theme.ts && rg -q "no" src/theme.ts && rg -q "star" src/theme.ts && rg -q "background|bg" src/theme.ts
  tags: [implemented]
- label: the naiou scaffold does not include skilled provider modules, dashboard data modules, Rust index backend, npm wrapper, or pypi wrapper
  command: test ! -e src/providers && test ! -e src/data.ts && test ! -e src/models.ts && test ! -e index && test ! -e npm && test ! -e pypi
  tags: [implemented]

## visuals
- label: the hyperspace renderer includes a createStarfield function adapted from opentui-candy using ThreeCliRenderer, Scene, PerspectiveCamera, and colored star streak geometry
  command: test -f src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "function createStarfield|const createStarfield" src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "ThreeCliRenderer" src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "PerspectiveCamera" src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "LineSegments|Points" src/hyperspace.ts
  tags: [implemented]
- when the agent resolves a decision, the hyperspace tunnel tints green for Yes and red for No before transitioning to the final scene @implemented
- after the decision tint, the final scene returns stars to normal colors and animates a shaded circular planet scaling into view with the decision text centered on it @implemented
- label: the hyperspace renderer updates camera aspect and renderer size on terminal resize
  command: test -f src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "setSize" src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "updateProjectionMatrix" src/hyperspace.ts
  tags: [implemented]
- label: the hyperspace renderer uses a frame callback loop and exposes cleanup that removes input and resize listeners and releases render resources
  command: test -f src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "setFrameCallback" src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "cleanup" src/hyperspace.ts
  tags: [implemented]
- the normal-space and hyperspace scenes draw visible stars or streaks directly in the OpenTUI buffer even when the Three renderer is unavailable or occluded @implemented
- the final planet uses shaded ASCII characters and renders the answer text as ASCII art on the planet @implemented
- the OpenTUI visual experience is rendered through the hyperspace ThreeCliRenderer scene rather than a separate BoxRenderable overlay @implemented
- question letters, cursor, status text, final planet, and answer text are scene objects inside the hyperspace renderer @implemented
- label: the TUI targets the original hyperspace scene budget of 30 fps rather than 60 fps
  command: test -f src/app.ts && rg -q "targetFps: 30" src/app.ts
  tags: [implemented]
- label: ASCII scene text uses contiguous block cells without visible gaps between lit pixels
  command: test -f src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "TEXT_CELL_FILL = 1" src/hyperspace.ts && ! rg -q "cellSize \* 0\.82" src/hyperspace.ts
  tags: [implemented]
- label: the final planet is rendered as a compact shaded ASCII disc grid instead of thousands of per-frame planet meshes
  command: test -f src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "PLANET_CELL_FILL" src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "buildPlanetRows" src/hyperspace.ts && ! rg -q "row = -15" src/hyperspace.ts
  tags: [implemented]
- label: hyperspace-phase ASCII and planet cells are batched with InstancedMesh instead of per-cell Mesh objects
  command: test -f src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "InstancedMesh" src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "setMatrixAt" src/hyperspace.ts && ! rg -q "const mesh = new Mesh\(geometry, material\)" src/hyperspace.ts
  tags: [implemented]
- label: the final planet scales against the visible viewport aspect and reaches roughly 80 percent of the available view
  command: test -f src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "planetScaleForViewport" src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "0\.8" src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "visibleSize\(camera" src/hyperspace.ts
  tags: [implemented]
- label: top and bottom captions are normal OpenTUI TextRenderable text rather than ASCII scene text
  command: test -f src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "TextRenderable" src/hyperspace.ts && rg -q "renderer.root.add" src/hyperspace.ts && ! rg -q "controlsText|statusText = createSceneText" src/hyperspace.ts
  tags: [implemented]

## agent
- label: the agent loads configuration from ${NAIOU_HOME:-~/.naiou}/config.json while preserving shell environment values as higher priority
  command: test -f src/agent.ts && rg -q "NAIOU_HOME|\\.naiou" src/agent.ts && rg -q "config.json" src/agent.ts && rg -q "process.env\[[^]]+\] \|\|=|process.env\.[A-Z0-9_]+ \|\|" src/agent.ts
  tags: [implemented]
- accepted yes/no questions resolve to exactly the string Yes or exactly the string No, with no extra text @implemented
- label: the chat-completions request constrains finalization through structured output using response_format JSON schema or a dedicated final-answer tool
  command: test -f src/agent.ts && (rg -q "response_format" src/agent.ts || rg -q "final[_-]answer|finalAnswer" src/agent.ts)
  tags: [implemented]
- label: the agent loop hot-loads tools from tools/*.mjs and executes tool calls between streaming chat-completions turns before finalizing
  command: test -f src/agent.ts && rg -q "tools" src/agent.ts && rg -q "\\.mjs" src/agent.ts && rg -q "tool_calls" src/agent.ts
  tags: [implemented]
- label: the agent sends native fetch requests to an OpenAI-compatible /v1/chat/completions endpoint and supports streaming SSE response parsing
  command: test -f src/agent.ts && rg -q "fetch" src/agent.ts && rg -q "/v1/chat/completions" src/agent.ts && rg -q "stream" src/agent.ts && rg -q "data: |TextDecoder|SSE" src/agent.ts
  tags: [implemented]
- label: the default bundled tools are safe read/explore tools and do not provide broad file write, shell execution, deletion, or process-spawn capability
  command: test -d tools && ! rg -q "writeFile|appendFile|rmSync|unlink|spawn|exec|Bun\.spawn|fetch\(" tools
  tags: [implemented]
- non-yes/no questions are refused by the same LLM-backed oracle instead of being forced into Yes or No @implemented

## flow
- launching naiou without a submitted question opens the full-screen OpenTUI app in a normal-space starfield input scene @implemented
- typed question text is rendered as large centered ASCII art constrained to roughly the central 70 percent of terminal width and height @implemented
- the input scene renders a blinking large ASCII cursor at the current question insertion point @implemented
- pressing Enter in the input scene freezes the question, starts the agent loop, and transitions the starfield into hyperspace cruise until the agent resolves @implemented
- while the agent is processing, a one-line muted grey status appears at the top edge without disrupting the centered question or hyperspace view @implemented
- label: the hyperspace phase machine uses Enter-submitted processing state instead of a Space key trigger to start motion
  command: test -f src/app.ts && rg -q "enter|return" src/app.ts && ! rg -q "Space: Engage Hyperdrive|key.name === .space.|name === .space." src/app.ts
  tags: [implemented]
- the blinking cursor is rendered separately from the question text so it does not affect ASCII text sizing or centering @implemented
- the final scene provides an Enter-to-ask-again path that resets the oracle to a fresh input scene @implemented

## testing
- label: integration tests document and execute facts, build, CLI, agent contract, safe tools, and TUI smoke coverage
  command: test -f tests/integration.md && test -f tests/agent.test.ts && bun test tests/agent.test.ts
  tags: [implemented]

# domain
- a question is the free-form user text displayed in the input scene before submission @implemented
- a decision is the final oracle value and has exactly two valid values: Yes and No @implemented
- processing is the interval after Enter submission and before the agent resolves a decision @implemented
- hyperspace is the animated processing visualization that cruises while processing and transitions after a decision @implemented

# ci

## release
- pushing a v* tag to the repository triggers the Release GitHub Actions workflow for cross-platform builds and publishing @spec @ci @implemented
- the Release workflow builds naiou binaries for four platforms using a matrix: linux-amd64 (ubuntu-latest), linux-arm64 (ubuntu-24.04-arm), darwin-arm64 (macos-latest), windows-amd64 (windows-latest) @spec @ci @implemented
- each build job sets up Bun via oven-sh/setup-bun, installs dependencies with bun install, and compiles the executable using bun build --compile src/main.ts --outfile naiou @spec @ci @implemented
- build jobs package the naiou binary into platform artifacts: .tar.gz for Unix (containing naiou), .zip for Windows (containing naiou.exe); no Rust indexer is included since naiou has none @spec @ci @implemented
- artifacts are uploaded via actions/upload-artifact@v4 with names like naiou-linux-amd64 etc. @spec @ci @implemented
- a release job runs after all builds, downloads all artifacts, and creates a GitHub Release using softprops/action-gh-release@v2 that includes the .tar.gz and .zip files plus generated release notes @spec @ci @implemented
- the workflow has no publish-npm or publish-pypi jobs; naiou intentionally omits npm and PyPI wrapper packages (per scaffold facts) @spec @ci @implemented
- the Release workflow requests contents: write permission at the top level for creating releases and uploading artifacts @spec @ci @implemented
- the workflow file lives at .github/workflows/release.yml and is the only workflow @spec @ci @implemented
- developers cut a release by creating a v*-prefixed git tag and pushing it (example: git tag v0.2.0 && git push origin v0.2.0) @spec @ci @implemented
- the only official mechanism for producing and publishing prebuilt naiou binaries for all supported platforms is pushing a v* tag, which executes .github/workflows/release.yml @spec @ci @implemented
- AGENTS.md documents the release process (how to trigger the workflow, what platforms are supported, and where artifacts appear) immediately after the core fact-driven development instructions @spec @ci @implemented
- prebuilt release artifacts use the naming convention naiou-{linux-amd64,linux-arm64,darwin-arm64,windows-amd64}.{tar.gz,zip} and are attached to the GitHub Release for the tag @spec @ci @implemented
- the project version is defined in two places that must be kept in sync: package.json and src/cli.ts (const VERSION) @spec @ci @implemented
- tests/integration.md contains a test that asserts the CLI --version output matches the current version string @spec @ci @implemented
- to prepare a release the version is bumped in package.json, src/cli.ts, and the expected value in tests/integration.md before tagging @spec @ci @implemented
- the first release after adding the GitHub release workflow is v0.2.0; it is performed locally by bumping version to 0.2.0 (package.json + src/cli.ts + tests), committing, and creating/pushing the v0.2.0 tag (remote must be configured to git@github.com:av/naiou.git or equivalent after the repo exists on GitHub) @spec @ci @implemented
- when no git remote named origin exists, the correct remote (git@github.com:av/naiou.git) is added before attempting push and tag push; push will only succeed after the GitHub repository has been created @spec @ci @implemented
- after the v0.2.0 tag is pushed, the Release workflow runs on GitHub and attaches naiou-*-* artifacts to the new GitHub Release @spec @ci @implemented
